You're clear on that, right?

492
00:33:10,855 --> 00:33:12,823
When people want
the best, they page me.

493
00:33:12,925 --> 00:33:15,575
I have basically been running
Dr. Chang's department...

494
00:33:15,677 --> 00:33:17,655
Dr. Chang has an
impeccable record!

495
00:33:17,679 --> 00:33:20,880
- He is a dinosaur!
- And so am I!

496
00:33:23,185 --> 00:33:24,817
You're...

497
00:33:25,587 --> 00:33:27,954
This is...

498
00:33:28,056 --> 00:33:30,890
- You're gonna regret this.
- Dr. Torres...

499
00:33:30,992 --> 00:33:33,593
No! No, no. I am just...

500
00:33:34,629 --> 00:33:36,296
No, I am excellent!

501
00:33:36,398 --> 00:33:38,278
I am excellent, and
any other hospital

502
00:33:38,333 --> 00:33:40,233
would be thrilled to have me.

503
00:33:40,335 --> 00:33:41,562
I'm flattered for
the offer, Larry,

504
00:33:41,586 --> 00:33:43,787
and I'm seriously
considering it.

505
00:33:43,889 --> 00:33:46,089
But it's complicated and
I need a little more time.

506
00:33:46,191 --> 00:33:48,403
I can't give you
more time, Derek.

507
00:33:48,427 --> 00:33:51,111
I can give you more
money, better benefits,

508
00:33:51,212 --> 00:33:53,692
and a whole lot of press.
That's what I can give you.

509
00:33:53,765 --> 00:33:56,661
- But I can't give you much more time.
- - Yes, I am.

510
00:33:56,685 --> 00:34:00,036
I'm a superstar, a
superstar with a scalpel!

511
00:34:00,138 --> 00:34:02,038
- Torres!
- No! Don't say my name.

512
00:34:02,140 --> 00:34:03,784
I am too big a star for
you to say my name.

513
00:34:03,808 --> 00:34:06,020
I build arms out of nothing

514
00:34:06,044 --> 00:34:07,510
and legs like God.

515
00:34:07,612 --> 00:34:10,781
And when I win the Harper Avery
and every other prize there is,

516
00:34:10,883 --> 00:34:13,633
you will rue this
day, Chief Webber.

517
00:34:13,735 --> 00:34:16,136
That's right. I said "rue."

518
00:34:18,056 --> 00:34:20,990
Tight ship you're
running here, Webber.

519
00:34:21,092 --> 00:34:22,392
Real tight ship.

520
00:34:58,963 --> 00:35:01,464
- Amanda. Hi.
- Hi.

521
00:35:01,566 --> 00:35:03,199
What are you doing here?

522
00:35:04,736 --> 00:35:07,537
I... can't sleep.

523
00:35:09,174 --> 00:35:14,460
I can't fall asleep, 'cause
I see his face all the time.

524
00:35:17,465 --> 00:35:20,117
I see him at bus stops.

525
00:35:20,219 --> 00:35:23,886
He was sweet,
smiling, and then...

526
00:35:23,972 --> 00:35:26,055
And then I see the
way that he ended up,

527
00:35:26,158 --> 00:35:28,724
so that even his best
friends can't recognize him

528
00:35:28,826 --> 00:35:30,160
and I can't sleep.

529
00:35:32,280 --> 00:35:34,581
Can you... Can you sleep?

530
00:35:35,033 --> 00:35:37,134
I...

531
00:35:37,236 --> 00:35:40,520
am gonna write
you a prescription...

532
00:35:40,622 --> 00:35:42,633
for an anti-anxiety medication.

533
00:35:42,657 --> 00:35:45,842
And I want you to take it
because the sleep deprivation thing

534
00:35:45,944 --> 00:35:47,611
can be quite harmful.

535
00:35:55,487 --> 00:35:57,031
- Dr. Robbins.
- Chief.

536
00:35:57,055 --> 00:36:00,356
Did you order an emergent
3-D MRI for this patient?

537
00:36:00,458 --> 00:36:02,442
OK, you're mad, I see that.

538
00:36:02,544 --> 00:36:04,310
But with the patient's
mother's insurance

539
00:36:04,412 --> 00:36:07,246
it could take weeks to get an
MRI and a specialty pain referral...

540
00:36:07,348 --> 00:36:10,683
So you expect the hospital
to pay with whose money?

541
00:36:10,786 --> 00:36:13,703
- Sir, I only thought...
- I don't want to hear it,
Dr. Robbins.

542
00:36:13,805 --> 00:36:16,272
Now discharge the patient,
refer him back to his physician,

543
00:36:16,374 --> 00:36:17,674
and do it now!

544
00:36:24,833 --> 00:36:27,233
Dr. Karev, change of plans.

545
00:36:33,208 --> 00:36:34,740
Open up!

546
00:36:36,812 --> 00:36:39,779
Open the door, Torres.

547
00:36:39,881 --> 00:36:42,782
Open the door, or
I'll keep knocking

548
00:36:42,884 --> 00:36:46,385
and potentially damage
my multi-million dollar hands.

549
00:36:46,487 --> 00:36:49,989
My ex-husband died.

550
00:36:50,091 --> 00:36:53,225
He died. He actually
got hit by a bus.

551
00:36:53,327 --> 00:36:57,447
George got hit by a bus, and
now I have to get a new job

552
00:36:57,549 --> 00:36:59,909
and I'm never gonna
see my friends anymore

553
00:36:59,984 --> 00:37:04,387
and Arizona keeps
bringing me donuts!

554
00:37:12,331 --> 00:37:14,080
This place for sale? It's nice.

555
00:37:16,384 --> 00:37:18,484
- What?
- Oh, nothing, nothing.

556
00:37:24,592 --> 00:37:26,392
Oh, my God!

557
00:37:26,494 --> 00:37:28,155
- Hey, Derek!
- Oh, hey, hi!

558
00:37:28,179 --> 00:37:31,881
- Dude, get a room.
- On the stairs? Doesn't that hurt?

559
00:37:31,983 --> 00:37:34,049
Leave us alone, we're newlyweds.

560
00:37:34,152 --> 00:37:36,419
A Post-It wedding does
not make you newlyweds.

561
00:37:36,521 --> 00:37:39,256
You know what?
You're newlyweds, too.

562
00:37:39,358 --> 00:37:42,108
- You need your own space.
- What are these?

563
00:37:42,210 --> 00:37:44,260
Keys to my trailer.
Your new home.

564
00:37:46,398 --> 00:37:47,797
Enjoy.

565
00:37:52,571 --> 00:37:54,471
- Dr. Hunt.
- Yes?

566
00:37:54,573 --> 00:37:57,390
I'm Louise O'Malley,
George's mother.

567
00:37:57,492 --> 00:38:00,610
Of course, I'm sorry.
I didn't... I'm sorry.

568
00:38:00,712 --> 00:38:02,128
It's all right.

569
00:38:02,230 --> 00:38:04,714
Well, I hope you don't mind
me coming here to see you.

570
00:38:04,816 --> 00:38:07,600
I know you surgeons
are very busy people.

571
00:38:07,702 --> 00:38:12,222
- My Georgie was always...
- That's no problem. It's fine.

572
00:38:12,324 --> 00:38:14,524
I'm...

573
00:38:15,560 --> 00:38:18,060
having trouble. I'm...

574
00:38:18,162 --> 00:38:19,896
having trouble...

575
00:38:21,533 --> 00:38:23,933
I...

576
00:38:24,035 --> 00:38:27,887
I think it's because I'm
having trouble understanding.

577
00:38:27,989 --> 00:38:30,084
There's a piece of
the puzzle missing.

578
00:38:30,108 --> 00:38:34,076
I do better when I understand
things, how things happen.

579
00:38:35,063 --> 00:38:38,798
And George, my George...

580
00:38:38,900 --> 00:38:40,644
The boy I knew,
the boy I raised,

581
00:38:40,668 --> 00:38:43,736
my boy, would never
have joined the Army.

582
00:38:43,838 --> 00:38:47,123
So I'm trying to understand.

583
00:38:47,225 --> 00:38:50,309
I'm trying to understand
that piece of it.

584
00:38:50,411 --> 00:38:53,646
I'm trying to understand why
Georgie wasn't at work that day,

585
00:38:53,749 --> 00:38:56,082
why he was on his
way to my house

586
00:38:56,184 --> 00:39:01,187
to tell me he joined
the Army in wartime.

587
00:39:02,624 --> 00:39:05,225
I don't understand.

588
00:39:05,326 --> 00:39:08,811
And Dr. Webber said
I should talk to you.

589
00:39:12,651 --> 00:39:14,562
Mrs. O'Malley, I didn't
know him like you knew him,

590
00:39:14,586 --> 00:39:16,085
didn't know him long,

591
00:39:16,187 --> 00:39:19,155
but he had tremendous
potential as a trauma surgeon.

592
00:39:19,257 --> 00:39:21,123
He was very fast on his feet.

593
00:39:21,226 --> 00:39:24,627
He could think and act
simultaneously under intense pressure.

594
00:39:24,730 --> 00:39:26,996
He had tremendous potential.

595
00:39:27,665 --> 00:39:29,499
And...

596
00:39:30,868 --> 00:39:34,137
He was impatient. He
wanted to become better faster.

597
00:39:34,239 --> 00:39:36,406
He wanted to save more lives.

598
00:39:37,909 --> 00:39:39,409
He was good.

599
00:39:41,145 --> 00:39:43,513
And he was thoughtful
and generous.

600
00:39:44,883 --> 00:39:47,366
Now, I think in
the end, I think...

601
00:39:48,136 --> 00:39:50,503
I think he was heroic and noble,

602
00:39:50,605 --> 00:39:52,755
and I liked him very much.

603
00:39:52,857 --> 00:39:58,011
And I think he gave you a good
reason to be very, very proud.

604
00:40:09,941 --> 00:40:11,808
Hey, I'm headed out.

605
00:40:11,910 --> 00:40:14,243
- Just wanted to say good night.
- Good night.

606
00:40:15,697 --> 00:40:18,509
Clara, you just moved... You
moved your fingers, like you waved.

607
00:40:18,533 --> 00:40:20,917
You waved goodbye. This is huge!

608
00:40:22,687 --> 00:40:26,055
That's huge? That I waved?

609
00:40:26,891 --> 00:40:28,608
That I waved a finger?

610
00:40:28,710 --> 00:40:30,292
That's my life from now on,

611
00:40:30,394 --> 00:40:32,896
that's the best I
have to hope for?

612
00:40:33,832 --> 00:40:37,434
Clara...

613
00:40:37,536 --> 00:40:40,519
Do you see that woman
out there talking to Dr. Hunt?

614
00:40:40,621 --> 00:40:44,156
We buried her son this week.

615
00:40:44,259 --> 00:40:47,343
He had an accident, like you.

616
00:40:47,445 --> 00:40:52,548
He wasn't even as bad off as
you were, and he didn't make it.

617
00:40:52,650 --> 00:40:55,418
Clara, I know that
it doesn't feel like it,

618
00:40:55,520 --> 00:40:57,803
but it is a miracle
that you lived.

619
00:40:57,905 --> 00:41:02,341
It is a miracle. So you
should call your mom.

620
00:41:02,443 --> 00:41:04,944
She would want
to know the truth.

621
00:41:07,699 --> 00:41:10,500
You stupid little bitch.

622
00:41:11,836 --> 00:41:14,504
You really don't get it, do you?

623
00:41:14,606 --> 00:41:16,706
You should have let me die.

624
00:41:16,808 --> 00:41:19,875
You had no business.

625
00:41:19,977 --> 00:41:24,880
I've got one working hand,
I may never walk again.

626
00:41:24,982 --> 00:41:30,186
Do you think you're God?
You had no business.

627
00:41:30,288 --> 00:41:34,223
Your friend is better
off. His mum is better off.

628
00:41:34,325 --> 00:41:38,962
Do you think this is a miracle?
Who wants to live like this?

629
00:41:39,063 --> 00:41:42,298
Just let me die! Just
let me die, please!

630
00:41:42,400 --> 00:41:44,634
- Just let me die!
- Hey, Clara...

631
00:41:44,736 --> 00:41:47,870
Just let me die! Get off me!

632
00:41:47,972 --> 00:41:49,422
I need some help in here!

633
00:41:49,524 --> 00:41:53,225
- Clara, stop! You have to stop!
- Get off me!

634
00:41:58,399 --> 00:42:00,719
<i>In medical school, we
have a hundred classes</i>

635
00:42:00,768 --> 00:42:03,869
<i>that teach us how
to fight off death...</i>

636
00:42:05,606 --> 00:42:08,341
<i>and not one lesson
in how to go on living.</i>
